Open Source Security Camera Threat Detection System
Iraj Kalia, Spring 2026
Introduction: 
The current security landscape has a technological divide that makes many organizations unsafe. On one side of the range are large enterprise companies that utilize advanced proprietary AI systems that provide real-time threat detection; however, these systems require expensive subscription costs as well as specialized on-site technological expertise, making them unaffordable for most organizations. On the other hand, are residential consumers who rely on easy-to-install and cloud-based security cameras that do not have the same level of performance or processing power to meet the needs of professional organizations. The result is that there is a large segment of mid-tier markets, such as small manufacturing plants, rural farms, and community non-profits, that are underserved. These markets are operating in high-risk environments but do not have a strong enough infrastructure or capital available to support enterprise-level contracts. Additionally, the lack of broadband access at remote locations makes traditional cloud-based AI detection solutions ineffective or unreliable.
This project is aimed at opening up high-quality security technologies via an open-source system and removing the idea that a professional standard can only be achieved by people with large amounts of money. The overall goal of this project is to provide an automated video-enabled system that can detect threats, connecting the advantages of high-end artificial intelligence to the limitations of resources available in niche markets. The system will work by using "Working Open" principles to prioritize processing occurring on-site and offer a reliable, open, and sustainable security system.
The two primary target markets for potential customers are: 1) small warehouses that need to have high levels of theft and tampering detection without having to rely on onsite guards; and 2) rural farming areas that need to maintain automated surveillance over their equipment and livestock where limited internet connectivity exists.
The project will also focus on providing municipalities with tools to retrofit existing structures with open-source, non-proprietary security systems that respect the local community’s privacy rights while also allowing for local control.

2. The Integrative Project Management Lifecycle
The methodology used in implementing the proposed system is the Integrative Project Management Lifecycle, which consists of four phases: Define, Design, Development and Production. The Integrative Project Management Lifecycle provides an organizational structure to develop the system and addresses the holistic implications that the system will have on the community that it impacts outside of just writing code. During the Define phase of the project, we created a detailed picture of what the completed project will look like. We determined both the high-level community goals as well as the technological goals that are needed to resolve the community issue addressed by the project. This is an extremely important phase for applications with a high-security requirement, as the Define phase will include creating a formal definition as to what constitutes a threat in a defined market/segment. For example, for an industrial warehouse, a "threat" could be defined as an unauthorized person entering the facility via a vehicle. In contrast, for a rural agricultural center, a "threat" may be defined as removing farm machinery from the premises or making livestock distressed.
During the design phase of a project, the definitions created during the previous phases are translated into functional workflow and product specifications. The design phase also includes mapping out the logic for how a video feed will be processed, buffered, and analyzed. The project defines technical standards early on to reduce late-in-the-project additions of features and ensure the project meets the user's primary requirements. After the design phase, the dev phase uses rapid prototyping and the Agile method of developing to build the Minimum Viable Product (MVP) that has the required functionality for taking a development approach to host development in publicly available repositories, which are used for version control and collaborative feedback. The final phase of the project's development consists of deploying a stable version 1.0 of the product into a controlled environment where the system’s performance can be evaluated in real time and refined based on actual user data, thus verifying that the development of the system is technically sound and practically useful when used in an actual security environment.
3. Agile DevSecOps and Algorithmic Ethics
The standard life-cycle models for developing security-sensitive systems are not sufficient to provide adequate assurance during the development stage. This project applies Agile DevSecOps principles and includes security as a priority that is woven into the total life-cycle of development. Rather than performing a security audit at the end of the development phase, the team will create security-sensitive stories and abuse cases in the first phase of the development process to proactively simulate and address common methods for unauthorized access, unauthorized video from spoofed video feeds, and unauthorized alteration of data while building the system. The project will employ automated testing frameworks such as Catch2 to ensure that every new feature or algorithm has been subject to rigorous testing for identified security vulnerabilities prior to it being placed into the production branch.
In addition to focusing on technical security, this project has an overarching commitment to transparent algorithmic rights management. Automated threat detection systems inherently carry the possibility of encoding social bias which may lead to discriminatory surveillance systems. To mitigate this risk, the project uses a "Privacy By Design" framework to ensure consideration of data protection before writing any code. The project also makes all detection models and training data available to the community for audit purposes, which gives interested parties the ability to review how "threats" are classified and defined. This level of transparency allows mid-tier clients (who require a high level of security but lack confidence in "black box" AI systems) to build trust in the project's methods for threat detection. By offering educational modules and documentation on detection methodologies, it will allow users to exercise their human agency when utilizing the automated system, thereby enabling them to modify or revise decisions made through artificial intelligence to better align with their own ethical and operational standards.

4. "Working Open" and Community Sustainability
The viability of an open-source project relies upon its capability to develop a sustainable ecosystem populated by developers, end users, and contributors. The Working Open philosophy emphasizes that both public documentation and collaborative governance are as important as the source code itself in establishing an open-source software project. The project leverages collaborative tools such as Github to coordinate international working groups that create, update, and maintain hardware standards and software updates. Additionally, the documentation is hosted on ReadtheDocs, which provides detailed, user-friendly setup instructions and troubleshooting guides to help users with limited technical skills install the system without needing specialized training.
The project uses Discourse trust levels to create a meritocratic system to uphold high-quality contributions from users, allowing established contributors and expert users to moderate and audit contributions so only high-quality code gets into the primary production repository (an example of crowdsourced quality control). This method of validating code in a system is very important with security software because the consequence of one bug could result in severe safety issues. Additionally, the project hosts biannual hackathons and quarterly Developer Sprints to bring external security researchers into the system to stress test the product. By accurately maintaining a complete inventory of every open-source component and providing public status reports, the project has a high level of transparency that proprietary systems cannot achieve. This product development strategy enhances the technical robustness of the product and establishes a highly resilient community ecosystem that can sustain development of the system for several years after the product's initial development cycle.
5. Technological Strategy: Risk, Debt, and the Hardware Pivot
One important strategy in managing technical projects is ensuring that technology choices are fully aligned to support long-term continuance of the project. The original specification of this project included specialized hardware interfaces such as FPGAs to allow for high-performance, deterministic video analytics. Although FPGAs provide the fastest processing speed available, they create a huge amount of technical debt and implementation risk within the mid-tier market. In addition, the specialized skill of developing software for FPGAs creates a barrier for the community to contribute to this effort, thereby creating hard debt on the implementation because the underlying logic will require the assistance of an expert to refactor or update. By shifting the focus of this project to "Edge AI" hardware (e.g., NVIDIA Jetson or Industrial NUC), we reduce this implementation risk and create a much more flexible and extensible software stack.
The impact of this technological shift on the project schedule is quite significant. By utilizing standardized software stacks, we can use higher-level programming languages such as Python and C++ to speed up the Dev phase of the project, because we will be able to take advantage of pre-existing software libraries for computer vision and machine learning. Accelerating the development process is essential to meeting our 16-week goal milestones and gives us more time at the end of the semester to do refinements and bug fixes. Also, using accessible technologies minimizes Supply Chain Risk. If a given FPGA module were not available any longer, it could delay the delivery of the project for several months; on the other hand, industrial-grade NUCs and Edge GPUs are readily available, so the project could continue on track even if we experienced localized hardware shortages.
6. Rescoping and Long-term Trade-offs
One of the most significant functions of the mid-term check-in during the project is evaluating, and most often re-evaluating, the viability of the project in its full cycle from start to finish in 16 weeks and thus re-scoping if necessary. Moving from using Field Programmable Gate Arrays (FPGAs) to more general-purpose Edge AI devices is a trade-off that weighs the super-specialized raw power of FPGAs against the more generic, community-maintainable systems. This re-scoping event reflects the maturity of a project manager as they acknowledge the constraints of resources in reaching the entire target market. For example, a warehouse manager can obtain more value out of a NUC-based system, which can be easily updated via a simple software revision, than from an FPGA board, which will result in having to use an electrical engineer to modify it. By re-scoping, the project will convert hard debt into soft debt, where technical complexity exists in the software layer as opposed to being in the actual circuit. The ability to convert hard debt to soft debt is beneficial because soft debt is far easier to repay via iterative refactoring and version-controlled changes in code on GitHub.
The long-term consequences of the rescoping plan goes hand in hand with working openly. A more software-oriented approach provides a wider selection of contributions from the community since there are far more developers who understand and can implement Python-based AI frameworks versus hardware synthesis. As a result, the project’s bus factor (the number of individuals who must be struck by a bus for the project to stall) is increased. Reducing any technical barriers to entry to the community results in a more sustainable system, meaning that the community will be able to continue maintaining and improving the threat detection aspects of the system well after the initial development teams are gone.
This strategic alignment of technology and community capability will ultimately deliver a robust, market-ready v1.0 product that provides the full power of modern AI technology while at the same time providing a practical and long-term solution for users.
7. The 16-Week Implementation Roadmap and Feature Set
The process of implementing the system follows a structure that will take place over a period of 16 weeks which will be divided into two halves. This will allow for a balance between creating new features and receiving user feedback while also working towards paying down your technical debt. The first half of the semester (Weeks 1 through 8) will be focused on completing the Define and Design phases, followed by developing the Minimum Viable Product, which will include five core detection features that will serve as a baseline for alerts across the industry. These features will include;
Digital Tripwire for perimeter monitoring.
Human vs. Vehicle Classification to reduce false alarms from wildlife or machinery.
Loitering Detection for time-sensitive security triggers.
Camera Tamper Alerts to detect occlusion or redirection.
Directional Movement Analysis to flag "wrong-way" entries in loading zones.
The second half of the project (Weeks 9-16) focuses on evaluating and iterating, where the alpha build is shared with stakeholders in the industrial and agricultural sectors. This period is critical for fine-tuning the first five features based on real-world data and fixing bugs identified in the sandbox environment. During this time, the team also implements two advanced features:
6. Object Left Behind for identifying unauthorized static items in clean zones.
7. Asset Removal Alerts to monitor high-value equipment.
